Documentation: Authorship/Ethics Guidelines,Participant/Recruitment Guidelines,Set-up Instructions,Recommended Participant Questionnaire (you can use your own if it collects all the necessary information)
authors: Teresa Flanagan (data collection and entry)
ethics: I have submitted an ethics approval and I am waiting to hear back and/or it is currently being revised.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When the official time for data collection ends, i.e., you will continue testing as many babies as you can until data collection closes for the ManyBabies1 project or you reach your alternative stopping date listed above.
gazefollowingstoppingother: Have not yet decided if participating in this portion
recruitmentmethod: Public community events (25%), children's museums (25%), Facebook / Google advertisements (25%), flyers at local businesses (10%), word of mouth (10%), hosted community events (speaker series, etc, 5%).
Screening:
All participants will have been entered into our database (Filemaker custom-build) and been given introductory information about the lab before being contacted for ManyBabies participation. 
This database is shared across three developmental labs and includes basic parent contact information, sibling information, gender, developmental disabilities, gestational age (37 week cutoff for 'full term'), list of previous studies they participated in, method of original recruitment, and basic linguistic input (if they have previously been in the lab).
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods),Undergraduates with a minimum grade point average (GPA)
Training:
All RAs are run through a scaffolded process as outlined in our lab manual. This process starts with fully reading the content of the lab manual, then running through federal background checks and either NIH or "Citi" ethics online training (certificates of completion are kept in the lab). RAs then move on to reading relevant literature and communicating with the PI about said literature, being trained by senior RAs on basic lab tasks (bringing families into the lab, calling to schedule families), and participating as 'sibling sitters' so they can observe consent being run by the PI. 
For eye tracking studies, the RA is trained on the appropriate software and given the ability to run through test sessions with other RAs or adults. Next, the RA watches 2-3 participants fully run by the PI, and, if available, watches videos of the PI or other RAs running the studies as well. Finally, the RA is given the opportunity to assist with parts of a real subject (e.g., starting up the eye tracking protocol with assistance) and to fully run a few pilot participants (normally, those who are either out of the targeted age range or who are preterm and thus could not be used in the final dataset).
TrainingCriteria:
As stated above, before running a 'real' participant the RA both partially-runs (assists) or fully runs pilot subjects with the PI in the room (or with the ability for the PI to watch video footage of the session with the RA afterwards). If the RA appears to be confident when interacting with families, proficient with the tracking software, consistent in their methodology, and comfortable interacting with babies after this scaffolded process, they are given permission to collect data independently. All sessions are video recorded (for screen media studies, with an HD webcam), and the PI randomly pulls these recordings to check for drift in methodology. 
Only two full-time fellowship students will be testing for the ManyBabies project this summer, both of whom have worked in the lab for a minimum of two semesters and have already been vetted as expert data collectors.
Eyetracking-specs: Tobii x3-120 tracker (120hz collection rate), mounted on a 25' Dell HD LCD monitor on a monitor arm. The tracker is connected to a high-powered Dell Precision M4800, with Tobii Studio primarily used as the data collection software (though more recently, Ogama has also been utilized).
Experimenter-location: In the same room but looking is coded offline-only or by eye-tracker
SoundAttenuation: Room in a quiet location in the building
Headphones: Stanley Sync Digital AM/FM/MP3 Radio Earmuff (RST-63012)
Decibel: They are set at a predetermined volume level on the computer, will need to check exact decibels.
Attachments: A copy of your ethics approval,A sample videorecording of the procedure being run (can be “dummy data” if you do not have permission to share from participants) - this may be distributed via Databrary if you have an account there.,A “walk through” video describing your lab set-up and greeting process. Please ensure that you have any needed video release forms for people who appear in your video. This is left to your judgment.

authors: Amanda Seidl
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StartDate: Our lab is pretty shut down from May 1st to May 15th because it's the break between sessions, so we will really start on May 15th
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod: In the past we have used published birth announcements in the newspaper, but recently the paper stopped publishing them, so we are in a time of recruitment flux. Our new method will involve placing return postcards in newborn infants' discharge packets. I cannot give estimates since I don't really know how well this will work.
Screening: Over the phone we ask about the speech/language status of infants' siblings, about episodes of otitis media, about whether they passed the newborn hearing screen, about due date and date of birth (to calculate term status), about birth weight, and about language experience. When infants come in we do an OAE test (less than 5 min) just to make sure they really do show normal hearing.
Ras: Graduate students only
Training: New graduate RAs observe the procedure for about 1 week. After 1 week of observation and playing with the procedure herself the RA will test a fake baby (an undergraduate pretending to be a baby) for about a week with supervision by other RAs (different ones). Then the new RA will test a pilot baby (usually one between age ranges currently being tested) while being observed by another RA. For a period of 2-3 months other RAs as well as the lab director will observe the new RA and provide feedback. During the year RAs take time to observe each other to provide feedback. After 1 year the RA is allowed to train new RAs.
TrainingCriteria: If neither the other RAs, nor the lab director see coding problems or problems describing the study or consenting caregivers the RA is ready to run, first under observation and then alone (as described above).
HPP-LR: We can specify this however we want, but I wrote the program to select randomly for light #1 and then to never repeat a side more than 2x.
BlinkRateOther: This is fully adjustable as well. I wrote it to be on .25 s and off .25 s every time it blinks.
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Sound-"proof" booth
Decibel: 72 db

authors:
Arielle Borovsky - PI
Megan Foley - research assistant
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
Notherprimary: We are collecting an N=32 of babies between the ages of 6-15 months.
recruitmentmethod:
Facebook announcements in online parent groups (25%),  library story-times (25%),  booths at community activities (50%)

Parents register their interest, and then we call them an complete an initial screening interview as they are entered into our registry.  Parents indicate simple age, language and other learning/health status information.   We then search our registry for families that are the right age and who have reported monolingual status and no other significant birth or health histories and contact those families to ask if they are interested in participating.
Screening: As stated above,  parents initially have registered their interest in taking part in research with their family via a general recruitment registry.   For this study, we will contact families with children within our anticipated age-range, and who are monolingual, 37+ weeks gestations, typically developing and normal hearing, as indicated by their initial responses when they signed up in the registry.     Parents will be called or emailed, and given a brief description of the experiment, and then asked if they are interested in taking part and scheduling within the next couple of weeks.
Ras: Undergraduates with a minimum grade point average (GPA),Undergraduates in an honours track only
Training: One undergraudate RA is responsible for testing in this project, and will complete this data collection as part of her honors thesis.   RAs in our lab shadow and observe multiple testing sessions with infants and toddlers, and participate in regular laboratory meetings where difficult testing situations and lab procedures are discussed.   For the ManyBabies1 project, this specific RA has been responsible for reading through the MB1 procedures, and, with the PI, has been programming the project on our eye-tracker.   She will then practice the procedure on multiple lab members, several friendly pilot families, and with the PI before being approved to initiate data collection by the PI.
TrainingCriteria: RA must first shadow numerous families, and practice the procedures with other lab members multiple times.  They are given increasing independence and opportunity to observe a variety of situations.  Before they can be a "lead" tester, they must first walk through all of the procedures with multiple senior lab members, and in most cases, with the PI of the lab.    They then test out the procedure with several designated "pilot" families, who are closely acquainted with the lab, and who provide honest and thorough feedback.   After discussing the feedback as a group in the lab, the RA is approved to begin testing by the PI

Documentation: Authorship/Ethics Guidelines,Participant/Recruitment Guidelines,Set-up Instructions,Recommended Participant Questionnaire (you can use your own if it collects all the necessary information)
authors: Gaye Soley (PI), Didar Karadag (Graduate student, who will be collecting data)
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod: We use a number of different strategies: hanging posters around the campus, distributing flyers on weekends at parks and shopping malls, posts on social media, or contacting mothers from gymboree classes. We also ask participating parents to give us contact information of other families with babies in similar age range.  The percentages vary quite a bit, but I'd say that the most of the babies we got so far, were through word of mouth - friends of mothers, who came to the lab. We do not do an initial screening, but we ask questions about the infant's development / health in our questionnaire and  if the baby does not meet our criteria for inclusion, we exclude the data of that baby after testing.
Screening: We do not have an initial screening process. We only collect information about the baby's gender and date of birth and decide whether to schedule the baby based solely on these two pieces of information. We collect these through various means I described in the previous section. Once the family is in, we give them a questionnaire that asks about whether the baby is full-term, typically developing, and has normal hearing. In addition, because most studies we conduct in the lab involves music perception, we ask whether the baby has frequent ear infection, whether there is a history of hearing problems in the family, whether the baby is exposed to unusual noise and whether he or she has cold on the day of testing. In addition, we ask some questions about the baby's language and music exposure. For the IDS study, we will be using the questionnaire provided.
compensationothertext: We give a certificate and either a t-shirt or a bib
Ras: Graduate students only
Training:
In our lab, only graduate students test infants. Because all ongoing studies in the lab require online coding, students go through a training and they have to become reliable in coding eye-gaze before starting testing infants. For this, we have a detailed written protocol about how to set up each infant study and how to code eye gaze. As a first step, students are asked to read this carefully.
Then, students and I first go through 1-2 experimental session videos from previous studies that were coded by me and I explain the technical details of the procedure. Then they have to code 3-4 videos that were previously coded. Some of these videos are more difficult to code than others (e.g., the infant is not very stable etc). Students' coding has to agree with at least 90% of the frames in all these videos. So far, I only had 2 graduate students who are involved in infant testing and both passed this training successfully. After this, students observe me while setting up and testing 3-4 babies. After this, they test at least 2-3 babies while I am present. If everything goes well, they start testing alone and they are assisted by an undergraduate RA. I also check the videos of the first couple of babies they test and code online to see if there are any problems.
TrainingCriteria: They have to code at least 3 videos from previous experimental sessions and have to agree at least on 90% of the frames. Then they have to watch while I (or another experienced researcher in the lab) test 3-4 babies. After this point, if the student feels ready to test babies, she/he can start testing under my supervision. If everything seems ok, I let the graduate students test infants by themselves with the help of an undergraduate RA. The graduate students who will be testing infants for the manybabies project have already tested about 20-30 babies each.
SS-Hardware: Habit
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Sound-attenuated chamber (i.e., room with really good insulation)

StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod:
mailouts via:
local nurseries (50%)
local baby groups (20%)
community organisations (10%)
local authority newsletter (10%)

in-person visits to children's centres (10%)
Screening: Initial invitation letters are sent to all families with children who fit the inclusion criteria, with brief procedural information and explicit information about inclusion criteria for the specific study, enabling eligible families to express their interest in participating. The family background questionnaire is included in this invitation letter, to be returned by email. If reasons for exclusion become apparent via their emailed questionnaire responses, we will inform the parent that they are not eligible and thank them for their interest. Those remaining eligible then schedule an appointment for testing and are sent practical information about visiting the lab. They will receive a reminder by text the day before their appointment
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods)
Training:
1.	RA reads full written protocols.
2.	The RA watches the walkthrough video alongside the PI.
3.	PI demonstrates to RA equipment set-up, operation, data transfer/back-up.
4.	RA roleplays the entire testing session with the PI in parent role and another lab member acting as the participant.
5.	PI discusses with the RA what they would do in a range of scenarios.
6.	RA observes PI run 2-3 pilot testing sessions.
7.	PI observes RA run 2-3 experimental testing sessions.
8.	PI continues to monitor RA in subsequent testing sessions by watching selected videorecordings.
TrainingCriteria:
Good performance in stages 4 - 6 above.
RA reports high level of confidence for testing sessions.
Eyetracking-specs: EyeLink1000Plus eye tracker. Experiment Builder generates the experiment running on a Windows PC.

ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod:
10% - flyers distributed to parents through community centres, public health
40% - recruitment through parenting tradeshows and family-friendly public festivals
40% - purchased lists of local parent contact information
10% - referrals, word of mouth
Screening: When parents are phoned, they are first asked to update their files by answering a few questions. These questions include specific screening questions for the study at hand. If the parent responses indicate that the infant is eligible, then they are given more information about the study and asked to participate.
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: New RAs are walked through each stage of the procedure carefully by a trained RA or trained graduate student/postdoc. After this, the trainer has the new RA pretend to be a parent with an infant, and runs them through the entire procedure. Then, they reverse roles, and the new RA "runs" the trainer through the experiment, providing feedback as needed. Once new RAs are trained, they will only run infants together with experienced RAs at hand.
TrainingCriteria: When the RA can run through the entire procedure without prompting or corrections, they are considered to be sufficiently trained. The infants are always run with an experienced RA present.
HPP-Hardware: Custom software on a Windows 7 Dell. 3 monitors in a double-walled soundbooth.
HPP-LR: Left and right alternate with each trial presentation
DeviationsText2:
Side of trial presentation is not going to be randomized across trials. Our software is restricted to alternate between left and right presentation. 
We also plan to test infant skin conductance during the experiment (already discussed with Michael Frank). This involves putting a wireless pack on the baby's ankle and attaching sensors to their foot. We are using Biopac equipment.
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Sound-"proof" booth
Decibel: 70 dBA using reference audio. We will need to submit our noise floor levels later. Our sound level metre does not test below 50dB, and will need to borrow one. I will email updated noise floor levels when acquired.

authors: Claire Delle Luche
ethics: I have submitted an ethics approval and I am waiting to hear back and/or it is currently being revised.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
gazefollowingstoppingrule: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod:
The Babylab database is used to contact volunteer parents of children within the right age bracket.
They are recruited at public events (children oriented fun and activity fairs), parent groups or library nursery rhyme times.
I don't have access to the precise statistics yet.
Screening:
We first only see the list of children of the right age within a set period of 2 weeks. If they are premature (< 37 weeks of gestation) or with reported hearing or developmental delay, we are not using their data. We may occasionally invite these excluded infants so that they can participate in a study as a thank you for their parent volunteering. These data are not kept in the final dataset.

We initially contact the parent/carer by its preferred method, email of phone. In the email, we briefly explain the aim of the study and the procedure, offering them to reply to us with a suggestion for a time and date that would suit them and their child's rhythm (especially for young infants, we ask them to choose a time when their child would typically be "happy"). The information and consent forms are attached.
If we have no response, we usually call the parent 3-4 days after the initial email. On the phone (including as first contact), we again explain who we are, why we are calling them and what the study entails. We offer to email the information and consent forms.
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods)
Training:
I am in charge of training the students.
1- I will explain the study and its procedure.
2- RA does the experiment as a "participant"
3- I show the procedure a few times
4- RA tries the procedure a few times with an adult as participant
5- I train the RA with the whole recruiting and booking process, often with "live demonstration" (= I make the phone calls and answer emails), then with close supervision (= RA does the process but I'm here for support and immediate feedback)
6- for the first child and until I am fully satisfied that procedure standards are perfectly respected and the RA is comfortable, I will be with the RA throughout the process.
TrainingCriteria:
1- confidence in the procedure, no error at any point (from recruitment to sorting out paperwork and data)
2- self confidence and at ease with the study and welcoming parent/child
SS-Hardware: Experiment builder
DeviationsText2:
We prefer children sitting on a highchair with the parent sitting right behind, but if the parent straightaway says the child would prefer being on her lap or if the child does not want to be sat on a highchair, we then immediately remove the high chair so that the child can be in their parent's lap. We record that information.

If children become unhappy and want to be on their parent's lap, we usually change but do not retain the data as there was an interruption.
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Room with occasional mild/moderate noise from adjacent room(s)
SAText1: we have some coating to prevent noise but while it is imperfect the room is located in a very quiet location, with little passage and activity.
Headphones: I have updated our headphones for the eardefender ear muff, as suggested here.
AnythingElse: I do not have access to a sound meter just yet, so this data is missing from the questionnaire. I was hoping for a way to save these responses before sending...

recruitmentmethod: We usually get information form the "Registre de l'État Civile" of Paris, they provide us information about the date of birth and the address of the parents. Each researcher then transmits to the lab-menagers the precise information about the date of birth of the group of infants she/he needs to test. We send 200 letters per research with an automatic protocol (Maileva) and we have a response averaging between the 10/20%. If with the 200 letters do we not reach the number of participants that we need, each experimenter can send other letters. For the older infants another system of recruitments is to use infants that have already come once to the lab and they are re-contacted. We also have a Facebook page and we use to distribute flyers to each parent.
Screening: Parents contact directly the person that is involved in the study (either by email or phone number) in order to discuss about the experiment and take an appointment. We use to asked parents: the date of birth, the language's exposure of the infants (estimating a percentage), if the infant is pre or full term (37+weeks). Due to the huge number of bi/trilingual infants in Paris, if the study is previewed for monolinguals, we use to redirect the infant to another experimenter. We do not ask before the visit about typically developing and normal hearing. We have this information only when the family arrive the day of the experiment.
compensationothertext: Diploma with a picture of the infants/family
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: RA will be involved only in the offline coding of the videos. The PI and the experimenter will teach them how to code the videos using the program that we use in the lab (PsyCode).
TrainingCriteria: RA will not run experiment. As for the offline coding, due to the experimenter's and the PI's previous experience in offline coding, one or both of them will also code a subset of the videos and will correlate the results with those of the RA. If about 90% correlations is achieved, the RA will be considered ready.

HPP-LR: specified order but with no more than 2 side repetitios on the same side in a row

ethics: I have a new ethics approval that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StartDate: Yes, just received ethics approval. Will start ASAP.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When the official time for data collection ends, i.e., you will continue testing as many babies as you can until data collection closes for the ManyBabies1 project or you reach your alternative stopping date listed above.
Notherprimary: 64 (one full block for Dr. Luke and one for myself)
recruitmentmethod: We mail invitations to participate in research via an agreement with state vital records. Just prior to the mailing, we ask the state vital records office to verify that no infants have died since we received the birth records. If any have, we do not mail to those parents. Ten to 15 percent of parents agree to participate. Parents indicate their interest in participating by returning a postage-paid postcard with their contact information.
Screening:
For this study, we are asking the following question by phone prior to scheduling an appointment. If the infant is not eligible for this study, we have other studies we can refer them to. 

What languages does your baby hear in the home? What percentage of time is each language spoken in front of your baby? [If the second language is spoken 25% of the time or more, refer the parent to other studies they might be eligible for.]

Was your baby born early? [If so] How early? [If more than two weeks, the baby is not eligible. Refer the parent to other studies they might be eligible for.]

Does your baby have any medical diagnoses? [If so] What is the diagnosis? [If the baby has any diagnoses that you are not sure would exclude the baby from this study or not, tell the parent you need to ask Dr. Lundwall and will call them back. Some examples of diagnoses that would be problematic are: Deafness, blindness, Angelman Syndrome, Cri du Chat Syndrome, Down Syndrome, Fragile X Syndrome, Klinefelter Syndrome, Neurofibromatosis, Prader-Willi Syndrome, Rett Syndrome, Smith Magenis Syndrome, Turner Syndrome, Velocardiofacial Syndrome, Williams Syndrome, or XXX Syndrome. The list is just for your reference, don’t read it to the parent.]
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods)
Rastext: Research Methods, CITI training, and Criminal Background checks (required by the state vital records office)
Training: In addition to Research Methods, CITI training, and Criminal Background checks (required by the state vital records office), I provide weekly mandatory lab meetings which cover one or more of the following: ethics, procedures, or relevant literature.
TrainingCriteria: They must read the procedures manual, watch another RA (or me) run the experiment 1-3 times, run the experiment several times while being observed by me or a trained RA, follow a protocol and document any exceptions or errors in following the protocol. We also periodically do protocol checks to verify the RA hasn't drifted from the procedures.
Eyetracking-specs: Tobii TX300 and Tobii Studio (Dr. Luke is handling the Eye Tracker)
Experimenter-location: In the same room but looking is coded offline-only or by eye-tracker
SoundAttenuation: Room in a quiet location in the building
Headphones: high-quality noise cancelling headphones with an audio mask (I think they are Bose QuietComfort 35 Wireless Headphones)
Decibel: 70 dBA using reference audio and typically 20 dBA without

authors: Jessica Hay (PI) and Sara Parvanezadeh Esfahani (graduate student, data collection and analysis)
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
gazefollowingstoppingrule: When the official time for data collection ends, i.e., you will continue testing as many babies as you can until data collection closes for the ManyBabies1 project or you reach your alternative stopping date listed above.
gazefollowing-method: central fixation/single screen with offline coding
recruitmentmethod:
Mailout via the Health department - 50%
Community events - 20%
Online (website, facebook, etc.) - 30%
Radio ad - new recruitment strategy
Screening:
We ask 4 eligibility questions before we schedule an infant for a study.
1- What is your child's due date?  If they are over 4 weeks early, they are ineligible to participate.  We correct for gestational age if they are born before their due date. For example, if we have a study starting at 6 months and an infant is born 2 weeks early, their eligibility for the study would begin at 6 months, 2 weeks.    
2- Does your child hear any languages other than English?  If so, how many hours per week on average?  If a infant hears over 10 hours of another language per week they are not eligible for a monolingual study.  
3 - Does your child have any hearing or vision problems, corrected or uncorrected?  Children with hearing problems or tubes are ineligible, even if they are corrected.  
4- How many ear infections has your child had in the past 12 months?  If they have had over 4, they are ineligible for the study.
compensationtext2: Books (any subsequent visit they get a book)
Ras: Graduate students only,Other
Training:
N/A Only graduate students or the lab manager will be testing infants for Many Babies. All experimenters have been running this methodology with other lab studies.  
Initial training for new experimenters begins with practicing coding on previously recorded experiments.  Once they become comfortable with coding, they will run 10-15 "practice" babies under supervision of a trained experimenter.  Trained experimenters will verify accuracy by checking videos of the "practice" babies.
TrainingCriteria: Although there is not typically a lot of conversation during an actual experiment, one of the criteria we use to determine a new experimenter is ready to test babies is whether they can participate in an unrelated conversation while they code a baby's looking behavior accurately.  To our mind, this indicates that the coding process has become automatized and the new experimenter is ready to test babies.  The graduate student running this study has run over 100 participants and the lab manager has run at least 20.
HPP-Hardware: Dell Optiplex 980 computer running Wisp on MatLab
HPP-LR: Random with no more than 2 on the same side in a row
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Sound-"proof" booth
Decibel: 71 dBA using reference audio, 28 dBA without

recruitmentmethod:
Boston Public Birth Records (they provide us with name of mother and infant, birthdate and address)
- We send mailings to all families we have records for (15% of infants that come in lab are from this recruitment method)
- Additionally through our peoplefinders.com website subscription, we look up phone numbers for all families, and then cold call all families we were able to find numbers for. (25% of infants that come in lab are from this recruitment method)

Fairs, Festivals, Markets 
- In the summers, we have recruit at fairs and festivals and public markets. We approach anyone with infants and children and ask people if they want to sign up to get an email. Via this method we recruit both infants and children. (5% of infants that come in lab are from this recruitment method)

Families that have come in previously with older siblings, friends of friends etc. 
- Majority of families that come into our lab have either come in previously with older siblings or have heard about us through word of mouth and call us that way (55% of infants that come in lab are from this recruitment method)

No screening happens at all through any of these recruitment processes
Screening:
New Families (that have never visited our lab before)
- We have no explicit screening process for new families, we welcome everyone to participate, then collect demographic information once they are in lab
- If their English is very poor and we are not able to communicate with them about our research and what they would be doing in our lab then we do not offer to find someone who speaks their native language and therefore forgo running these families

Old Families (that have visited our lab before and from who we have demographic information)
- We do not recruit infants that we know from previous demographic questionnaire that are premature, have any type of developmental delay or hearing loss
- If our study requires infants to be monolingual english only, then we do not recruit bilingual infants
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained,Other
RAsOtherText: Any level but we do have an application process, not all applicant get accepted
Training:
All RA's follow multiple trainings led by our lab manager on the following:
- how to use our database (for recruitment of families)
- how to set up all paperwork for families visiting our lab
- how to consent, debrief and interact with family
- how to set up infant studies generally (since most of our study use the same method)

After following training:
- read our RA manual that has explicit scripts for things like consenting and recruitment
- they shadow atleast one family being run by a graduate student/lab manager/experienced RA. At this point they are also first told how to code infant looking (press x button when infant looks here) and practice as second coder just to get a sense of how this works.
- they practice setting up for a fake family and lab manager/grad student reviews this with them
- they practice consenting/debriefing with lab manager/grad student
- they practice what to tell parents of infants in testing room in terms of not interfering in study etc.
- they run 3 families with graduate student/lab manager/experienced RA shadowing them and who are told to jump in when things are forgotten or mistakes are made

Offline coding (we recode all videos after the study is run to check reliability of online coding)
- RA's follow training and are asked to read manual.
- In training grad students code a few trials, then watch RA's code a few trials
TrainingCriteria:
They have to have followed all trainings mentioned above

Online coding
- In terms of coding infant looking, they are the second coder with experienced coder being first coder until they have coded 3 babies where their overall reliability across the study above 85%, with no single trial falling below 50%. 

Offline coding
- They have to get overall reliability above 85%, with no single trial falling below 50% for 3 videos that have already been coded by experience coder(s)

recruitmentmethod: All of our babies are recruited in the same way. Through a provincial agency we get permission to have access to names,addresses & phone numbers of parents who had a baby in recent months.  We send them a letter and follow with a phone call. Babies that are severely premature or very low birth weight are removed before we get the birth lists.  In our initial screening ( at the phone call) we screen out infants with major health problems. We gather info at the initial phone call that can be used to determine if baby is full term or premature, which will defined differently depending on the study they participate in. If parents cannot communicate in either French or English they will get screened to as we will not be able to accommodate their linguistic needs.
Screening: As mentioned above after parents get a letter we call them.  The calling is done by trained students who are fluent in French and English.  Student callers are well trained to be professional,respectful,  positive, and friendly.  If parents are not interested in participating at this initial phone call we are not permitted to call them back. If they are interested in participating we gather general information (age,gender of child, birth date, due date, language use in the home, any health issue with the child, any known hearing problems, also info on siblings) .  As  mentioned above if the parent cannot communicate either french or english they would not be recruited because we cannot accommodate them linguistically.
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: Students are interviewed by the PI and other lab members before joining as a paid or volunteer.   They are required to complete the infant recruitment training sessions so that understand the recruitment process and our obligations wrt protecting subject confidentiality. This includes an on-line ethics  training required by the Canadian funding agencies.  They are required to read papers on basic infant speech perception methods and publications from the lab and any documents related to the project they are working on. They observe an experienced tester doing infant data collection and  they practice making looking time judgments with video recordings of sessions.   When both the trainer and the student feels ready he/she will begin to take on testing in steps (e.g greeting parents and doing consent etc.) . When both feel ready the student will begin testing pilot subjects under supervision of the trained tester.  When the student and trainer feel that the student has mastered the process, he/she will begin testing subjects that will be counted as real subjects, first under supervision,  and then on their own.
TrainingCriteria: The trainer (and the student) has to be confident that the student has mastered and fully understands all of the steps involved and could troupe-shoot problems or glitches that may arise. The trainer will be someone who has a vested interest in the project, i.e they are either a research student or the lab PI.  Typically the student also has a vested interest in the study, i.e. they are not just an employee.
HPP-Hardware: We have custom software that we developed for running HPP.
HPP-LR: we specify this int he set-up. typically it is semi-random with no more than 2 on the same side in a row
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Sound-"proof" booth
Decibel: 72 dbA using reference audio ;  37dBA without (measured w/checkmate CM-130 SPL meter #100608096)

AnythingElse:
FYI. Since we are testing the oldest group, we are planning to complete the language questionnaire AFTER the testing because it takes some time (w/bilingual infants) and it can be difficult for the baby to transition from playing in the wait area (while we complete the questionnaire) to the testing room which is less interesting.  Also if they get involved with a toy we have to take it from them to go into the test room and that is not optimal for test cooperation. 

We also let babies keep a pacifier if they need it to be calm and attentive.  If they don't need it and are playing with it we suggest to mom that they not use it unless she thinks that they will fuss without it.

authors:
Martin Zettersten
Jenny Saffran
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod:
- Internet (40%): We post ads/ information on sites frequented by parents in the area (Facebook sites, blogs directed towards parents)
- Email (20%): university list serve to students/ faculty 3 times annually 
- Mailed letters (15%): We obtain addresses for mailing from birth registry lists screened for location (typically families who reside within our county, but sometimes criteria are within 30 miles of lab) 
- University pediatric clinics (10%): information is handed out at 6 month well visit check to all families
- Posters/flyers (5%): We display posters and flyers locally (clinics, day care/community settings, libraries, coffee shops, etc.)
- Children's Museum (5%): We conduct research at a local children's museum and simultaneously recruit families (very small percentage)
- Recruitment at local community events (5%): We set up a small stand at some local community events
- Newspaper (negligible percentage): Ads in local and community papers

We conduct no preliminary sample screening to determine basic eligibility.
Screening:
We typically contact families via phone or email when child is near the age of a study being run. (Usually search starting .5 month prior to eligibility and .5 month prior to age out to allow for scheduling.). 

We always ask the following screening questions:
- Has your child had any ear infections in the last 12 months?
- How many days before or after their due date was your child born? 
- Does your child hear any languages besides English on a regular basis? If so, how many hours per week (of non-English language)? 
- Does your child have any hearing or vision concerns?

In our lab, our *typical* practice is to treat babies as "practice" participants (i.e. exclude them from our sample), if one of the following is true:
- They have had 4 or more ear infections in the last 12 months.
- They were born 28 days or more before their due date (36+ weeks gestational age)
- They have had 10 hours + per week of language exposure other than English.
- There are significant concerns regarding vision or hearing.

For the ManyBabies study, we will ask the same questions for our records, but we will follow the exclusionary criteria laid out in the manual:
- We will NOT exclude any participants based on ear infections.
- We will require 37 weeks (NOT 36 weeks) gestation.
- We will exclude participants based on the 90% language exposure criterion from the ManyBabies manual, as assessed by the ManyBabies "Family Background Questionnaire".
compensationtext2: 1 book (Option 1 - families choose ONE of three options).
cashtext: $10.00 (Option 2 - families choose ONE of three options).
compensationothertext: Lab T-Shirt (Option 3 - families choose ONE of three options).
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training:
All training RA's meet with the lab manager to discuss the Head Turn Preference procedure. This typically involves explaining the method, showing an example with them playing the "baby" in the experiment booth and showing them an example from outside the experiment booth. Trainees then sit in on multiple Head Turn appointments as observers throughout training.

5 preselected videos are then coded by the trainee as if they were watching them live. After each video, reliability of their coding responses is checked via comparison of overall left and right looking button press times to the coding key. RAs should achieve 95% agreement with the key. The training videos are subsequently discussed with an experienced Head Turn coder (typically the lab manager) to allow for questions and look at differences and identify any issues.

"Practice" babies (i.e. babies who do not meet our inclusion criteria) are then scheduled for the trainee to run. The lab manager or senior experimenter will oversee/supervise and discuss at least 2 of these appointments. After this, once an RA feels comfortable running practice participants and if no other issues are identified, RAs move on to running typical participants.
TrainingCriteria:
- 95% agreement with the coding key on 5 preselected training videos
 - Experience running at least 2 "practice" participants under supervision, with no issues.
HPP-Hardware: WISP
HPP-LR: Random with not more than 2 on the same side in a row
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room

recruitmentmethod: We receive lists of all babies born in Paris and the surrounding departments from the French National Archives.  When an experimenter is looking to test infants from a specific age group, he/she will pick out roughly 200 infants from the list who fit the age criteria and send them a recruitment letter.  This is our exclusive form of recruitment.  If caregivers agree to be added to our database, they may be contacted at a later date to participate in a different experiment. For this Many Babies, we may use many children from the database, because the response rate of these parents is much higher and we can screen for the eligibility criteria.
Screening: Once parents have received the letter, they contact the experimenter or lab manager.  A quick summary of the experiment is given and if the parents have any questions, they are addressed at this time. Parents are reassured that the procedure is not dangerous and that they will be with their infant the entire time. They are asked for the child's birthday, name, and the parent's general contact information. In our typical recruitment, language background is noted (% exposed to each language). For Many Babies, we will also ask on the phone for length of gestation (37+ weeks is our cut-off) and whether the child has normal hearing.  Regarding whether the child is "typically developing", this is rather strange to ask on the telephone in France.  Typically, if the child has an atypical development, parents volunteer this information (e.g. reduced gray matter, blood transfusion, surgery, etc.). For Many Babies, we will ask a general question regarding the child's development and then follow up for more details at the experiment appointment.
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: We do not have RAs in our laboratory.  A post-doc (Katie Von Holzen) will test babies.  She has already completed projects with the HPP method. When she learned this method, she observed other experimenters testing babies, and then she practiced with colleagues, adjusting with feedback until she felt she was ready to begin.
TrainingCriteria: Experimenters are deemed ready to begin after a final run-through of the experiment with Thierry, checking their coding and the experimental procedure.

HPP-LR: Two, pre-determined random lists per order with no more than 2 on the same side in a row. The two lists are opposites of one another. The first four trials always present IDS once on the left and once on the right and the same for ADS.

ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
gazefollowingstoppingrule: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod: The vast majority of infants are recruited from mailouts/phone calls to families on government birth lists of all infants born within a particular geographic region (~95%).  Additional recruitment of siblings of those infants, and via community organizations, childcare centres, etc. (5%).
Screening: On the phone, we ask parents to estimate their children’s percent exposure to each language over their lifetime, and ask about any health concerns.  Only once infants come to the lab, parents complete additional questionnaires that include specific questions about gestation, hearing, and developmental problems, and to complete a structured interview that estimates language exposure.  Any infant who comes to the lab participates in the study if the family would like, whether or not they meet inclusion criteria.
compensationothertext: T-shirt for first lab visits, option for reusable snack bag for returning participants
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: RAs who test infants begin with an initial period of shadowing/assisting already-trained testers.  For undergraduate students, this phase typically lasts for several months.  Exceptional undergraduates (mostly honours track students) and graduate students are then trained by the lab manager on how to test infants.  Students begin by reading lab instruction documents regarding questionnaires, interacting with parents, equipment, etc.  They then complete mock test sessions with the lab manager, taking increasing level of independence.  Once they are able to follow lab protocol in mock tests sessions to a high level, they begin leading the test sessions for real infants while accompanied by an experienced tester who provides support and gives feedback.  Once the other testers and lab manager are satisfied that the prospective tester follows lab protocols, they begin testing on their own.  Training refreshers are provided each semester for all students who test infants.
TrainingCriteria: Consensus from lab manager, testers, and the PI that the new RA is able to follow lab protocols.  This is demonstrated when the tester is consistently able to test infants following lab protocol without intervention or feedback from senior testers.
Eyetracking-specs: Tobii T60-XL running Tobii Studio.  jHab run on a separate laptop to implement infant-controlled trial length.
DeviationsText2: Attention getters will be ended by experimenter judgment that the infant has fixated for approximately 1-2 seconds, rather than precise measurement of the fixation time to the attention getter .  This is because Tobii Studio cannot implement looking-contingent trial length, and this is difficult to coordinate with jHab.

ethics: Other
Ethics-other: We have ethics approval to cover the project and are writing a small amendment to add items to our demographics form from the ManyBabies1 Family Background questionnaire.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod:
brochures and flyers distributed in neighbourhoods, community centres, child care centres, notice boards, etc.
setting up recruitment table to hand out brochures at events e.g., "baby expo", local events for children, etc.
Screening: Parents usually call or email us (often filling out a sign-up form on our website). We respond giving them general information about what happens in a study in our lab, and ask them for basic information about themselves and their child: name of child and one guardian, contact details, child's date of birth, sex, birth weight, weeks early or late, how they found out about us, and whether they have any other children they may want to participate with. We then let them know that we will be in touch when we have a study for their child's age group, or if we have one then we tell them about the specifics and try to schedule. All other information is typically requested in our demographics form during the appointment, but for the ManyBabies project we will ask for language information during the initial study-specific scheduling contact.
Compensationtext: we have a free parking spot for participants
compensationtext2: parent can choose a toy or other gift for their child (shirts, ducks, etc.)
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: This study will be conducted by an undergraduate RA who has been in the lab for 7 months and has experience contributing to multiple studies as an actor, online and offline coder, etc. The lab manager (a member of the lab for the past year) will sometimes serve as online coder for the project and has extensive experience with this task. The PI will train the RA to use Habit software to conduct the study, we will practice using another volunteer RA as a "test baby", and all procedures will be checked before beginning to run the study.
TrainingCriteria: RA has to have run through the study with either the PI or lab manager present to show that she is familiar with all aspects of the procedure and is comfortable introducing parents and infants to the study. The first baby is always run with either the PI or lab manager present, and this person gives feedback to the RA afterward on anything to improve or anything that went wrong. We also run pilot babies to check the procedure and training before starting the official study. In this case we plan to run 2 pilot babies for this purpose.
SS-Hardware: Visual stimuli will be presented using a Sony 55" LED TV screen. Audio stimuli will be presented using a Behringer MS16 Active Monitor Speaker Pair. Stimulus presentation and coding will be done using the software Habit on either an iMac or Mac Mini computer. Video of the infant is recorded using a Canon Legria HF G25 HD camera at 1080i60, and video of the stimulus screen is recorded using a Canon Legria HF R606 HD camera. The two camera recordings are mixed in real time using a Kramer scaler.

Headphones: We will either use KAT KTU126 Ultra Isolation Headphones or Sennheiser HD280 Pro Headphones

authors: Janet Werker; Alexis Black (both involved in both studies)
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: Other
StoppingCriterionPrimary1: We will commit to 16, but will continue testing up to 32/when data collection closes (whichever comes first)
recruitmentmethod: We are one of six research centers that make up the Early Development Research Group at UBC; together we have a part-time staff member who recruits families with newborn babies at the local hospital for inclusion in a shared database.  Families of babies born with serious complications or before 35 weeks gestation are not approached by the recruiter. At the time of recruitment, details regarding the infant’s language environment, gestation, and health are noted for the database. We also recruit families through word-of-mouth and through advertisements at the local Science Museum or those placed at community infant development events – in those cases, families would sign-up online or would phone the EDRG office or one of the six labs directly. Approximately 88% of recruitment is achieved through the hospital; the remaining sources make up 22%.
Screening: When a study is in need of participants, undergraduate Research Assistants (RAs) use the database to find and reach out to families with babies who meet the study requirements (e.g. using the DOB, gestation, language exposure, and diagnoses fields on the database).  RAs first call the parents; if they are unable to reach the parent by phone, they send an email.  RAs briefly remind the parent how they originally signed up for the database and what the Early Development Research Group is. They ask if the parent is interested in participating in a study and if so, they verify the infant’s date of birth and language exposure before booking the study. It is important to note that these studies are held at the university, which is at the edge of Vancouver, and so the potentially long travel distance may be a factor in determining which families agree to participate.
Ras: Undergraduates with a minimum grade point average (GPA),Other
RAsOtherText: some experience with developmental psychology (e.g. through relevant coursework); ability to provide at least one positive and relevant reference; ability to commit to working 9 hours per week.
Training: A senior graduate student will be running the experiment for ManyBabies1 and ManyBabies1B. Trained RAs will be recruiting families.  This training is approximately 36 hours (9 hours per week for 4 weeks), under the supervision of the lab’s full-time Research Manager, and involves training in database management and how to communicate with families.
TrainingCriteria:
NA, in terms of testing babies
Upon successful completion of the training protocols described above, the lab’s Research Manager gives an RA approval to begin contacting families.

OtherlookingTimeText: Offline, human-coded, infant-controlled trial length (i.e. E-prime automatically logs the total duration of looks; off-line coding can account for look-aways that last less than 2 sec - and so don't end a trial)

ethics: I have a new ethics approval that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod: the city of Munich provides us with a database of all the families in the areas. We contact via mail the families that will have children in our age range at the time of the testings. We generally consider that the 5% will contact us back for an appointment. So, for instance, for 20 children we send letters to 400 families.
Screening: Interested families contact us back through telephone or e-mail. We contact them via phone or a-mail to make sure that they meet the inclusion criteria for the study, and we make an appointment with them. We also have a separate database of "returning families", that is, families that participated in a previous study and consent to be contacted again for future studies. We contact these families directly through phone or e-mail (thus skipping the first recruitment step).
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: Both RAs worked with the eye-tracker previously, so they knew the software. First the RA try the procedure with one another (one plays the participant) under my supervision. Then, each RA tests 3 pilot children.
TrainingCriteria: I am present during the trainings. They can start piloting when they know the procedure. I am also present during the pilot and give them feedback. If before the third pilot they are still making mistakes, they train with each other again before proceeding to the last pilot.
Eyetracking-specs: Tobii TX300 with Tobii studio + JHab for timing the trials
DeviationsText2: since Tobii studio does not allow infant-controlled trial length, we also use JHab to measure the looking time and proceed to the next trial when we are sure that the child was looking away for more than two seconds. To be sure, we look both at the child through the camera and at a window displaying the contact of the eye tracker with che child's eyes. When the child is clearly looking away from the camera AND neither of the two eyes are visible on the eye tracker status window, we start counting the two seconds. If then we see from the camera that the child is looking at the screen again OR one of the two eyes appear again in the eye tracker status window, we stop counting the two seconds. We do this in order to make the task more sustainable for children, so that they can go through more trials.
Experimenter-location: In the same room as the participant (please specify the kind of headphones worn by the experimenter and/or other blinding measures)
SoundAttenuation: Room in a quiet location in the building
OtherlookingTimeText: as previously described, we code the looking time through an eye tracker but the trial lenght is controlled online by the experimenter using both video information and eye tracking status and JHab to count the time
Decibel: 68.5 dBA using reference audio. I haven't measured the dBA without. I will do it as soon as possible and edit this field.

Screening: Initial contact for participants is generally made at a recruiting event or via our website/facebook.  At an event, located at a zoo, park, or other public venue, lab members offer the option for families to take contact info and reach out to us, or they can sign up on an email/calling list. Our website and facebook contains links to our eligibility questionnaire. Once this is filled out, we can determine whether an infant meets the criteria for participation. If they are eligible, a lab member makes contact via email or phone with a parent, describes the general task of a study, and asks if the family is interested in participating. Once the potential participant confirms interest in participating, a lab member works with them to find a time and day that works to carry out the appropriate study.  At the time of scheduling, Additional directions are given including parking details, a link to the MCDI is sent (with the option of being filled out 48 hours before, or at the time of the study), and the opportunity is given to ask additional questions. One day before the study, the parent is called to confirm that they still plan on participating.
Ras: Undergraduates in an honours track only,Graduate students only,Other
Training: RAs shadow a grad student or lab manager who are experienced running studies. After watching several participants, the RA and a grad student do several practice run throughs where the grad student pretends to be a parent/participant. Following this, the RA begins running the study with a grad student or lab manager present to make sure everything is being done properly. After the RA runs several participants with grad student supervision and follows all procedure correctly, they are allowed to run participants on their own. The training of RAs occurs during piloting of the study.
TrainingCriteria: An RA is determined sufficiently trained to test babies after the grad student/lab manager over seeing them has observed them running at least 2 participants properly.

visiting family groups

Screening:
Parents complete an online sign up form asking for details about the child's age, any developmental disorders, prematurity, language background.

Before inviting families in these notes are screened and only children that meet the includion criteria are contacted to be invited to take part. Families are emailed and given the opportunity to book a time to come in or decline to participate on this occasion. Choosing not to participate does not influence the likelihood that they will be invited to participate in other studies.
cashtext: £10 to cover travel and parking costs
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods)
Rastext: students completing an internship prior to embarking on their final year of study and students completing a dissertation as part of their final year. All have completed modules on child development during their second year course
Training:
Prior to any children coming into the lab students are familiarised and given extensive training with the equipment and study practising on each other and other members of the lab. Experienced researchers act as 'difficult' children to prepare students for the fact that it won't always be easy.
Once they are familiar with the techniques pilot participants are recruited for testing, these do not contribute data to the final sample. This gives trainees the opportunity to explain the study to someone naive and run the session with children prior to testing included participants.These pilot children's data are never included in the final analyses.
The first participant to be included in the dataset is tested with supervision and an experienced researcher is always available for any testing sessions being run.
TrainingCriteria: RA's need to satisfy experienced researchers, typically the project lead, that they have the necessary knowledge and skills to deal with any situations that arise appropriately and have the confidence that they will know when to seek support from more senior lab members.

authors: Erin E. Hannon, Karli M. Nave
ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When the official time for data collection ends, i.e., you will continue testing as many babies as you can until data collection closes for the ManyBabies1 project or you reach your alternative stopping date listed above.
recruitmentmethod: These statistics were calculated based on participant sign-up feedback, where we ask how they heard about us: Facebook page/advertisements (25%), Craigslist (25%), Campus Emails (17%), Community Outreach Events (i.e. attending Mommy Mixers, Trunk or Treat events, etc.) (9%), Fliers (6%), Word-of-Mouth (5%), Students (4%), Website (3%), Other (i.e. Referrals from other labs, Meet-up groups, etc.) (6%). No sample screening occurs during this process.
Screening: Once a family fills out our participation form (https://faculty.unlv.edu/ehannon/participate.html) or contacts us directly, we add them to our Participant Database (managed with Filemaker Pro). An RA typically follows up with an email or phone call thanking them for their interest and requesting further information about the child (due date, hearing status, etc.), and if the child is eligible for a study based on age we will schedule them to visit the lab. If a child is not eligible, we inform them that we will call them when the child becomes eligible for a study. For most studies in the lab, we collect information about due date and developmental and hearing status either over the phone or through our demographic/auditory experience questionnaire, but for one-visit studies we typically schedule and run children who are more than 3 weeks premature or who are not typically developing and if necessarily exclude them from the main sample later, analyze them separately, or control for these variables in the analysis. For the Many Babies project we will screen them based on age, due date, and hearing/developmental status whenever possible over the phone and before scheduling them for a visit. In the case that we accidentally test a child who does not meet eligibility criteria we will submit the data anyway and treat the child as a discard .
Compensationtext: We have a parking spot designated for our research lab.
compensationtext2: Infants receive a onesie with our "UNLV Music Lab" logo on it, a baby item (i.e. bib, bottle, baby toy, baby book, etc.), stuffed animal, or beanie hat (with lab logo)
introcredittext: This occasionally happens if the parent/caregiver is a psychology student enrolled in PSY101.
compensationothertext: Every child receives a Child Scientist Degree (First lab visit: Bachelor's, Second lab Visit: Masters, Third Lab Visit: PhD, Fourth Lab Visit: Post Doc...up through Full Professor)
Ras: Graduate students only
Training: Graduate students always run infant studies in our lab, so RAs will not be trained on running ManyBabies1. Before a graduate student runs an infant study, they shadow a well-trained graduate student or the Primary Investigator (Erin Hannon) live-coding an infant study at least three times, and then they are shadowed while they code an infant live. A trained graduate student oversees all training and is present at all times during testing.
TrainingCriteria: Trained graduate students and/or the PI carefully monitor training and are charged with deciding when a new graduate student is ready to test babies. They must demonstrate attention to detail and accuracy when coding pre-recorded infant videos before being okayed to run Many Babies1. Then, they must shadow a graduate student running the study at least 3 times before performing any live-coding. Finally, once the graduate student is sufficiently trained, s/he is allowed to code infant looks during an experiment.

recruitmentmethod: We mainly recruit babies via face-to-face interaction with parents at parenting tradeshows. We also use internet bulletin boards, and some parents come via person connections. I would say about 80% of the participants are from the parenting tradeshows.
Screening: We set up a desk at the parenting tradshows with a large sign board. Parents who stop by our desk hear a brief explanation about our laboratory and we answer questions if they have any. If they show interest, they sign up their name and receives a promotional gift for signing up (e.g. a bib). We then follow them up with a phone call, at which point some of the parents withdraw their participation. We get a lot of interest from parents who are concerned about the child's development. We tell them we are not experts on speech/language pathology but do not exclude them from participation based on their concerns. We also tell them the experiment we participate as a laboratory requires the baby to be a monolingual full term and if they meet these criteria they are invited to participate.
Ras: Other
Training: A postdoctoral research whose expertise is in the area of infants speech perception is in charge of testing all participants for the ManyBabies 1 project. This, however, is her first time running HPP using a new software in a new environment, so she used many sessions of pilot babies to make sure the overall experimental scheme works as it should. The PI oversaw the entire process with her. Undergraduate and graduate RA's also actively participated in the process and are well trained but we decided it will be the postdoctoral researcher who actually test the babies given this study is one of the first studies being conducted after the establishment of the lab.
TrainingCriteria: Since the postdoctoral researcher is already trained in testing babies, she decided on her own when to stop piloting the babies and move on to the actual testing in close consultation with the PI.

ethics: I have a new ethics approval that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
gazefollowingstoppingrule: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod: The main source of recruitment (approx 95%) is mailout via governmental birth-records database. The remaining 5% is families volunteering based on word of mouth and occasional Facebook adds
Screening: Mums are
compensationothertext: Small toy gift/t-shirt for the baby.
Ras: Must have an undergraduate degree
Training:
At CDC RAs are full-time employes and are NOT students at CEU. They rarely test infants on their own. In most cases, infants are tested by researcher who is the primary author of the study (PhD students/postdocs, at times also junior faculty) assisted by an RA. Exceptions are when: (1) the researcher speaks Hungarian and thus does not need assistance of an RA, (2) RA tests on her own (currently all RAs are female), because of researcher's illness or travel, but only if this is agreed on in advance, (3) a procedure is developed with involvement of the RA and researcher is not needed at all for data collection (e.g. because the procedure relies on an interaction between a toddler and Hungarian-speaking RAs). Consequently over the course of their employment RAs gain extensive training in assisting with and sometimes running-first hand various methodologies.

For ManyBabies we follow this standard model of data-acquisition at CDC. Most babies will be tested by MIkołaj Hernik (Associate Research Fellow with over 9 years of infancy research) assisted by an RA with over 3 years of experience in assisting with  (and occasionally running) infants studies at CDC, including working with the EyeLink eyetracker.

The procedure of ManyBabies was piloted with about 10 12-15-month-olds in order for both the researcher and the RA to get acquainted with procedure elements not common in our typical procedures (e.g. blinding mums with headphones) and to get a sense of older-babies behavior in the task.

When the researcher (MH) is not available for testing, some babies may be tested by the RA, who typically assists in the study, assisted by an RA in training.
TrainingCriteria: See previous answer. Typically an RA is has already considerable experience running some infant paradigms. If the method is new, the study is often preceded by a small pilot which may last until the procedure goes smoothly. RAs in training typical start by shadowing experienced RAs and then start assisting with a limited number of studies.

ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When you have tested the specific number of babies listed for each age group as indicated below (note that N includes all babies, regardless of whether they complete the study or fuss out)
recruitmentmethod:
Written invitation letter that is sent to parents based on birth record provided by neighboring cities.
Approximately 30% of the invited parents take part to one or more of the ongoing studies in our lab.
Before to schedule any appointment, we check for gestational age and birth weight, in order to exclude babies for preterm birth, and auditory and/or visual deficits.
Ras: Must have an undergraduate degree,Graduate students only
Training: Each new RA spends a couple of week observing the recruitment and testing sessions of the project in which he/she will be involved (or other projects if available). When the lab manager is available the RA receives a short training focused on the recruitment procedures and lab rules. If the lab manager is unavailable, the same training is provided by a “senior” graduate student. The RA is then trained for 1/2 months (depending on the number of available babies) by a senior researcher, typically a Phd student, in the online coding of babies' behavior. As part of the training, the first 2/3 online coding performed by the RA are reviewed offline by the senior researcher and the RA using the video recordings of the testing sessions.
TrainingCriteria:

recruitmentmethod:
Our on-campus lab primarily recruits via Facebook (50%), tradeshows (30%), and community posters (e.g., libraries, community centres, etc.; 20%). No sample screening occurs until the parent contacts us. We then ask about prematurity and hearing problems.

However, we will be opening a museum-based lab this week. This is where the Many Babies studies will take place. Therefore, we will have direct recruitment from the Museum floor only (although the new lab will be promoted in the media). We will screen for hearing or general developmental problems via questions to the parent.
Screening:
For our campus recruitment, when a parent sign ups for our database online, we ask about birthdate and due date via our online form. Therefore, we know about gestation from that information. We also ask about their exposure to their languages on our online sign-up form. Once they are in our database, we send an email to thank them. Once they are eligible for a study, we then email and confirm birth date, due date, and language exposure. At that point, we also ask about any hearing or developmental difficulties. 

For the museum recruitment, we will ask all the above questions in the lab itself.
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods),Undergraduates with a minimum grade point average (GPA)
Training: We have few testers in the lab. Most undergraduates are only coders/helpers. But, undergraduates with a developmental background and high GPA can become testers, especially if they are in Honours. We currently have three undergraduate testers: one hired RA, one senior volunteer, and one Honours student. First, the RA has to read the associated Ethics submission and a target article. Then, I or my senior graduate student trains the undergraduate RA by going over the entire experiment from start to finish. We then run a trial experiment with one of us as the "participant". Then, for the RA's first couple of actual experiments, they shadow a graduate student. After all this, they are ready to run on their own. All the same applies to graduate students as well (there are 3 graduate student testers in the lab currently). For the museum lab, all the above applies as well, but there will be more testers than our on-campus lab.
TrainingCriteria: As mentioned above, they need to have read the relevant materials, run a test experiment, and shadowed a senior member of the lab. Barring any major issues (e.g., a persistent misunderstanding of methods), they are then ready to test.

Check whether the child meets these criteria.
