recruitmentmethod: Infants are recruited through the University of Oregon's Team Duckling Developmental Database. Team Duckling is a group of researchers at the UO who study child development. We attend events in the community and invite families to sign up for the database. All infants in the ManyBabies sample will be recruited from this database.
Screening: We confirm infants' date of birth with parents (to ensure they are in the correct age range). We additionally ask if the infant was born withing two to three weeks of their due date, about any pregnancy/birth complications, and whether the infant hears languages other than English at home (and, if so, what percentage of the other language).
compensationtext2: They are invited to choose a book from our collection.
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained,Undergraduates with a minimum grade point average (GPA)
GPAtext: Prefably closer to 4.0, but not below 3.0.
Training: RAs practice coding videos of infants' participating in looking time studies. We first discuss coding (i.e., what counts as "looking") and code one or two videos together. They then code two videos on their own and we check for reliability (compared to an "expert" coder). We then discuss any inconsistencies. RAs then code three more videos on their own and we check reliability again. If reliability is less than 90% (i.e., they are missing more than 10% of looks), we again discuss discrepancies and they code three more videos on their own. At that time, if they have not reached 90% reliability they are assigned to a different project.
TrainingCriteria: When they have completed training (at least 5 videos coded on their own) and have reached 90% agreement.

recruitmentmethod: We send out mailers to parents who have recently had a baby in Knox County and surrounding areas each month. Our response rate is approximately 7% from these mailers. We also engage in recruitment events in the local community (e.g., booths at farmers markets, baby expos, etc.).
Screening: We make phone calls and send recruitment emails  with a general description of the specific project. We exclude infants who were born preterm (< 37 weeks gestation) or experienced any pre- or post-natal complications.
Ras: Undergraduates with specific coursework (e.g. child development, research methods)
Training: RAs have to complete compliance training and general training in eye-tracking testing in the lab. Before we run ManyBabies1 participants, we will do specific training for ManyBabies1 sessions. Only graduate students are allowed to "run" the experiment and manage the testing session.
TrainingCriteria: Undergraduate RAs are mostly involved in menial tasks during testing. They are monitored during training, and they are only allowed to shadow fully trained RAs until they demonstrate competence.

authors:

ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
EndDate: It’s not. Our stopping rule is when we’ve reached target N.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: Other
StoppingCriterionPrimary1: When we have tested the total number of recruited babies. Recruitment will aim for the N indicated below. Due to overbooking to compensate for potential appointment cancellations, this may include 1-5 additional babies beyond our specified N. Data from these additional babies will be collected and submitted. In addition, we aim to pilot with 1-2 babies. Their data will only be inspected to check that everything is order. All babies tested from Saturday March 3 2018 onwards “count” (i.e., are not pilot).
Bil-Langs: There will be lots of IndoEuropean second languages (English, Italian, Spanish); and probably some from former colonies and protectorates (languages of Senegal, Vietnam)
recruitmentmethod: Our primary source of infant recruitment is the National Civil Registry, who send us all the contacts of every baby born in the city of Paris. We then mail families to invite them to register in our database to participate in our studies. We have about 10% of positive answers. Then, when we have a study for the appropriate age of a given child, we send emails to the families who have registered their infants in our database.
Screening: Once a family has given permission to be added to our database, they provide additional information about their infant, including weeks of gestation, percentage of exposure to other languages, and hearing impairments. Based on the specific profile needed for each experiment, we search the database and contact the required number of families by e-mail or by phone. We then provide a brief description of the study and send them the consent form (and any other relevant forms) by e-mail, and arrange an appointment for them to come to the lab. The recruitment is usually done by the BabyLab manager.
compensationothertext: “Diploma” for participation with picture of the child
Ras: Graduate students only,Other
RAsOtherText: This is not formally required. There simply are no UGs around here.
Training: Every person who tests is first trained by our manager (who holds a permanent position and has worked at this babylab for over 10 years). She covers basic aspects of interacting with baby and the family. For central fixation and eye-tracking, we also train each other, typically an older student explains a newer one how to run everything. For both, there are typically some adult pilots before the person tests. Once they start testing, they are always accompanied by the lab Manager until she feels the person can function independently. Importantly, only two types of people test: Graduate students & postdocs (who gather data for their own studies), or (more rarely and not for the MB studies) professional RAs.
TrainingCriteria: Once they start testing, they are always accompanied by the lab Manager until she feels the person can function independently. We do not have a specific procedure for this.
Eyetracking-specs: an EyeLink 1000 eye-tracker; sampling rate 500 hz. Presentation using experiment builder
Experimenter-location: Other
ExperimenterLocationOtherText: The experimenter is right outside the sound-proof cabin (model cabine audiométrique IAC). Typically we only hear muffled sounds.
SoundAttenuation: Sound-"proof" booth
Attachments: A copy of your demographics questionnaire if you are not using the recommended form.,A copy of your ethics approval
AnythingElse:
We got the presentation files from the Reading group, and we thought they had been thoroughly tested. However, during adult pilots yesterday and a baby pilot today, we noticed it's not running as it should: trials are not stopped when participant looks to shoes/curtains, ceiling.... only if participant looks at the edges of the screen. We also note that trial is launched only if participant stares at center of screen for more than 2s, rather than if looks anywhere on the screen. We are now re-reading all the materials to check whether these decisions are based on recommended procedure, and if not, we'll change the minimum look to 500 ms, and the off to also include complete aways. 

This may also mean that we start data collection after what was noted above.

ethics: I have ethics approval on an existing protocol or an amendment to an existing protocol that will cover the ManyBabies1 study.
StoppingCriterionPrimary: When the official time for data collection ends, i.e., you will continue testing as many babies as you can until data collection closes for the ManyBabies1 project or you reach your alternative stopping date listed above.
recruitmentmethod: mailout through municipality
Screening: We check whether the baby is monolingual Dutch and is in the age group we are testing
Ras: Any level (including undergraduates of any level) as long as they are appropriately trained
Training: The RA is instructed by an experienced lab person (PhD student). They go through the entire procedure, from welcoming to saying goodbye, and practice this 'dry' first. This includes making the lab ready for the experiment, turning on the computer, checking the lights and the script, performing the experiment and saving the data. When the RA performs well in the 'dry' training sessions, s/he accompanies the PhD student in a couple of real sessions, and will take on more and more of the tasks in the procedure. Only if the RA feels comfortable with the procedure, and the experienced lab person is convinced that the RA is ready for it, the RA will start testing babies on his/her own.
TrainingCriteria:
RA feels comfortable with the procedure
RA has shown in 'dry' and then in real sessions that s/he knows how to welcome the parent/child, how to run the experiment and store the data, and how to handle the forms, reimbursement and book.
HPP-Hardware: AOC PCs, E-prime, 3 lights and speakers
HPP-LR: We specified 4 different left/right orders
Experimenter-location: In a separate control room
SoundAttenuation: Sound-"proof" booth
DataType: Offline, human-coded, fixed trial length (Please provide information about your coding practices/software)
OfflineText: ELAN, coding head-turns of at least 30 degrees as a "head-turn"
Decibel: 79 dBA using reference audio (65 dBA when we present the stimuli!), 38 dBA without

We recruit infants at a public infant health checkup in a public childcare center. We explain our studies roughly to their mothers then, and mothers who are interested in our studies register theirself as participants via a paper, e-mail, or telephone.
We ask infant's birth weight, gestational age at delivery, and developmental problems via a questionnaire.

Training:
RAs are not doing the testing but I will give them the manual translated into Japanese and explain the whole procedures.
And, I stress that the most important thing is infants and mothers are relaxed and enjoy the visit.
TrainingCriteria:
In this study, I will not ask RAs to test babies.
However, my criteria are remembering whole procedures, understanding the importance of reporting irregular events, and doing the testing in a relaxed state.
